\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {28}{\ignorespaces Electronic offset of the magnetometer as a function of position along the length of the center of the magnetic shield. Only the two transverse dimensions are shown. \textit  {\textbf  {Top.}} The $B_x$ component of the magnetic field measured with the sensor in its usual orientation ($B_{x,\delimiter "3222378 }$) compared to the sensor rotated upside down ($B_{x,\delimiter "3223379 }$). \textit  {\textbf  {Middle.}} Subtracting the two curves in the upper plot cancels the electronic offset that is presumed constant during the time it takes to measure the two traces. \textit  {\textbf  {Bottom.}} The sum of the two traces extracts the electronic offset only, since the actual field seen by the sensor cancels out to the extent that the sensor was rotated upside down precisely, assuming the field has not changed significantly during the sensor reversal and re-measurement.\relax }}{104}{figure.caption.68}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{offsetcal}{{28}{104}{Electronic offset of the magnetometer as a function of position along the length of the center of the magnetic shield. Only the two transverse dimensions are shown. \part {Top} The $B_x$ component of the magnetic field measured with the sensor in its usual orientation ($B_{x,\uparrow }$) compared to the sensor rotated upside down ($B_{x,\downarrow }$). \part {Middle} Subtracting the two curves in the upper plot cancels the electronic offset that is presumed constant during the time it takes to measure the two traces. \part {Bottom} The sum of the two traces extracts the electronic offset only, since the actual field seen by the sensor cancels out to the extent that the sensor was rotated upside down precisely, assuming the field has not changed significantly during the sensor reversal and re-measurement.\relax }{figure.caption.68}{}}
